**Synchronous Methods** block execution until the operation completes. The program waits for the file operation to finish before moving to the next line.

```javascript
const fs = require('fs');
// Synchronous - blocks execution
const data = fs.readFileSync('file.txt', 'utf-8');
console.log(data);          // printed first
console.log('After read');  // printed second
```

**Asynchronous Methods** do not block execution. They accept a callback function that is called when the operation completes, allowing the program to continue executing.

```javascript
const fs = require('fs');
// Asynchronous - non-blocking
fs.readFile('file.txt', 'utf-8', (err, data) => {
  if (err) throw err;
  console.log(data);          // printed last
});
console.log('After read');    // printed first
```

**Key Difference**: Synchronous methods are simpler but block the event loop. Asynchronous methods are preferred for performance in production Node.js applications since they don't block other operations.

