Step-by-step process to connect Mongoose and insert a document:

Step 1: Install required packages
  npm install mongoose express

Step 2: Require mongoose in your Node.js file
  const mongoose = require('mongoose');

Step 3: Connect to MongoDB using mongoose.connect()
  mongoose.connect('mongodb://localhost:27017/mydb', {
    useNewUrlParser: true,
    useUnifiedTopology: true
  }).then(() => console.log('Connected to MongoDB'))
    .catch(err => console.log('Connection Error:', err));

Step 4: Define a Schema using mongoose.Schema
  const userSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
    name: { type: String, required: true },
    age: Number,
    email: String
  });

Step 5: Create a Model from the Schema
  const User = mongoose.model('User', userSchema);
  // This creates a collection named 'users' in MongoDB

Step 6: Create a new document instance and save it
  const newUser = new User({
    name: 'Alice',
    age: 25,
    email: 'alice@example.com'
  });

  newUser.save()
    .then(doc => console.log('Inserted:', doc))
    .catch(err => console.log('Error:', err));

Note: mongoose.model() automatically creates the collection (plural, lowercase of model name) if it doesn't exist.

